snippet.textDisplay: I watch Raw, Smackdown and AEW from day 1. I tried watching Smackdown from the performance center last Friday night. I couldn't stand it. Turned it off before the Women's division match was even half finished. Couldn't bring myself to watch Raw at all. When AEW had to do the same format, I was like oh no, but after the opening discussion with Cody, I watched the whole thing. It was absolutely awesome!!!! I love how all of the wrestlers interacted with each other during the matches. Very cool having some of the other wrestlers, sitting in the seats and making it seem like you were in the Arena with them. Not gonna lie, the way you pulled this off, made me almost glad that the fans weren't there. Great freaking job!!!!

snippet.textDisplay: With AEW's recent big reveals of Brody Lee (formerly Luke Harper) as the Dark Order's "exalted one", the "broken" Matt Hardy as the fifth member of Cody's Elite in the fight against the likes of Jericho and Swagger with Inner Circle, and the current champion being none other than Moxley (formerly Dean Ambrose), AEW certainly has enough star power to generate quite public interest.  But the difference between WWE and AEW is how those stars are utilized in relation to the rest of the roster.  The building of factions is one of the most strategic plays in elevating as many superstars as possible out of the highly gifted roster.
